Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Pick the @rosemary{1/2%bunch} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm wedges (no need to peel) and pop onto a lined #baking tray{}. Add a splash of @oil{a splash}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and the chopped rosemary. Use your hands to rub the flavours all over the wedges. Arrange in one layer and roast in the middle of your oven until golden, ~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

In a #mixing bowl{}, mix the @panko breadcrumbs{30%g} with the @smoked paprika{1}(to taste) and a splash of @oil{a splash} making sure the crumbs are evenly coated. Season the crumbs with salt and pepper and keep to one side. Line another baking tray with #baking paper{}. Pat the @coley fillets{2} dry with #kitchen paper{} and then arrange the fish on the tray.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash you hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

Season the fish with salt and pepper. Spoon half the @garlic mayonnaise{2} onto the coley, dividing it equally and spread it over evenly. Carefully sprinkle the breadcrumbs onto each fillet, covering the mayo, then press the crumbs on making sure they stick. Keep to one side.

Ten minutes before the wedges are done, bake the fish on the top shelf of your oven until the crumb is golden and crunchy and the fish is cooked through.

> The fish is cooked when the centre is opaque.

When the fish has ~{3-4%minutes} left in the oven, heat a splash of @oil{a splash} in a #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. When the oil is hot, add the @Tenderstem® Broccoli{150%g} and stir-fry for ~{1%minute}. Season with salt and pepper and add a splash of @water{}. Cover with a tight fitting #lid{} or #foil{} and cook until the broccoli is tender, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Share the potato wedges and tenderstem between your plates and carefully place the coley alongside. Finish with a dollop of remaining garlic mayo. Tuck in!